.SH NAME
\fB²DPROG² \- DICOM import\fR: reads DICOM files, converts them to PNG images and records their metadata in a MariaDB database
.br
(manpage-Hilfe in deutsch verfügbar: 'man -Lde ²DPROG²')
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fB²DPROG² [-<shortopt>|--<longopt> [<supplement>]] ...\fR
.SH SHORT DESCRIPTION
\fB²DPROG²\fR is a command line program that reads DICOM files (Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine) from a configurable source directory, converts them into PNG images using \fBdcmj2pnm\fR, stores the images in a target directory and writes the relevant metadata of each file into a MariaDB database table.
.br
After processing, the original files are moved into an archive directory named after the import timestamp.
.br
The program is suited for regular, automated retrieval of DICOM images, e.g. from an ultrasound device, and their structured storage in a patient database.
.SH INSTALLATION
.br
First, please read the chapters 'Functionality', 'Preconditions', 'Automatically installed software packages' and 'Implications' below. Then, if connected to the internet, call (e.g. by copying the line and pasting it into a terminal):
.br
\fBN=²DPROG²;P=${N}_inst.sh;cd ~;wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/²gitv²/$N/master/install.sh -O$P&&sh $P\fR
.br
At last, call:
.br
 \fB²DPROG²\fR
.br
and answer some questions of the program.
.SH USAGE
Ideally, the program should have installed itself after the first call(s) and one-time answering of some questions in a self-running way.
.br
The program is typically called periodically via \fBcron\fR. It then checks the source directory (default: \fB/var/spool/dicomneu\fR) for new DICOM files. Found files are processed and afterwards moved to the archive directory (default: \fB/var/spool/dicomalt\fR) under a subdirectory named after the current date and time.
.br
The generated PNG images are placed in the target directory (default: \fB/var/spool/dicomziel\fR) and in the second target directory (default: \fB/var/spool/dicomziel2\fR), there sorted into subdirectories by year of acquisition.
.br
The metadata of each image (patient name, birth date, patient ID, sex, image type, physician, transducer, program, acquisition date, import date, UID) are stored in the configurable database table (default: \fBdictab\fR).
.br
If a file is already present in the database, it is skipped by default (option \fB-nm\fR changes this behaviour).
